      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2011_Solutions_2011s_page_003_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "It remains to show that if either l = 3 or l is a prime greater than 5, then l occurs at most six times as an element of a triple in S. Note that (p, q, r) ∈ S if and only if q2 − 4pr = a2 for some integer a; in particular, since 4pr ≥ 16, this forces q ≥ 5. In particular, q is odd, as then is a, and so q2 = a2 ≡ 1 (mod 8); consequently, one of p, r must equal 2. If r = 2, then 8p = q2 − a2 = (q + a)(q − a); since both factors are of the same sign and their sum is the positive number 2q, both factors are positive. Since they are also both even, we have q + a ∈ {2, 4, 2p,4p} and so q ∈ {2p + 1, p + 2}. Similarly, if p = 2, then q ∈ {2r + 1, r + 2}. Consequently, l occurs at most twice as many times as there are prime numbers in the list",
        "bbox": [
          0.12705882352941175,
          0.42303030303030303,
          0.49098039215686273,
          0.6254545454545455
        ],
        "order": 13
      }
    ]
  },
